As for ginseng, only because something has been used by the Chinese or some other ancient culture for thousands of years doesn't mean it's good or does what it says it does. Mandrake root won't make women fertile or men more potent because it "looks" like a naked woman. Likewise, the stars won't predict or dictate one's life because the universe was not made for us and they were not put in place by some fictitious deity to guide our lives. There is no "as below as it is above" in real life, only in people's ignorant imaginations.

Number one food trend in my household: rice and legumes! Like five varieties of rice! Basmati, jasmine, whole grain, random cheap "long grain", and delicious delicious red rice. Aaall of the legumes! snippet.textDisplay:
What!!! That's not how ginseng colors work at all. The colors are a result of different ways of processing it.

White/tan is naturally dried
Red is steamed (older roots aren't destroyed as easily in this process)

https://www.dec.ny.gov/animals/7474.html

Color is also used to describe different varieties and species of ginseng, "Red Ginseng" is Asian Ginseng, or *Panax Ginseng*, and white is often (although not always) American Ginseng, or *Panax quinquefolius*. Other loosely related non-ginseng (*Panax*) species are often called different kinds of ginseng as well.

- A mildly peeved ecologist with a bit of botany background.
